  "chunk_index": 34,
  "summary": "Jimmy Sycamore, Eileen Bündel, and Bunty discuss Jimmy's recent investigations into the \"seven o'clock\" mystery. Jimmy reveals he has discovered a small bottle containing a mysterious white powder, though he refuses to explain its origin. The conversation turns to a nearly burned glove that Detective Bettman had previously asked Jimmy to try on. Bündel observes that because Jimmy's right hand is bandaged, the large glove must have been worn on his left hand. She concludes that Bettman used the glove's size as a distraction to conceal the fact that the shooter was left-handed.\n\nJimmy recalls that Sir Oswald Cutt is ambidextrous, noting that Sir Oswald dealt cards left-handed during a bridge game at the chimney house on the night Gary Wade died. The group speculates that Sir Oswald may be connected to the \"seven o'clock\" mystery and the events at the Double Dragon Church, suggesting he might have orchestrated a farce to avoid suspicion. They also recall Inspector Bettman plucking ivy from the millionaire's coat, wondering if the inspector had suspected him from the beginning.\n\nElsewhere, Lord Kettlemere, who is attempting to hide a wrist injury, receives a visit from George Lomax. George expresses his desire to speak with Eileen Bündel, praising her maturity, intelligence, and ambition. He declares his intention to marry her, arguing that despite their age difference, he can provide her with a respectable social position and that their union would be mutually beneficial.",
